> From 73277.620@compuserve.com  Wed Mar 24 15:23:54 1993
> Date: 24 Mar 93 11:59:13 EST
> From: Steve Allen <73277.620@CompuServe.COM>
> Subject: Norton Diskreet header info
> Message-Id: <930324165912_73277.620_EHB48-1@CompuServe.COM>
> 
> I'm sending an email msg because although I can read the usenet
> posts, I can't reply via usenet.
> I've taken a look at Diskreet, and can tell you that for every file
> encoded with Diskreet, the first 16 bytes are a header that id the
> file as Diskreet data, and the 2nd 16 bytes are the encoded string
> "ABCDEFGHENRIXYZ", with null-term. Following that is 13 bytes for
> the null-term filename, followed by some other stuff, including the
> filesize, and possibly the date. There ain't anything there that
> looks like a password.
>    It's common practice to put a checksum in the first bytes of the
> file, so you can test the password for accuracy. This appears to be
> what Norton has done here.
>    By the by, Norton uses CBC mode. However, the IV is always the
> same. Thus the similarity in the data from the two files with the
> same password.
>    I think that if I were Symantic, I'd assume that people were
> disassembling my code left and right, and any trapdoor would be
> quickly exposed. Such an exposure would kill that carefully
> nurtured confidence in the Norton name, and possibly kill Symantic
> as well. So, I don't think there's a trapdoor. I don't know, I just
> don't think so.
>    If you would be so kind as to post this msg to sci.crypt (and
> all other conferences where your original msg appeared) for me, I'd
> be much obliged.
> -Steve Allen (73277.620@compuserve.com)
